In the [[Elections in Norway|Norwegian parliamentary election]]s, the Socialist Left Party has been able to hold the position as the fourth-largest party in Norway, behind the [[right wing]] [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]], [[Conservative Party of Norway|Conservative Party]] and the [[centre-left]] [[Norwegian Labour Party|Labour Party]].<ref name="<U+00E5>ttinitotusenogni">{{cite web | author = | title = Stemmefordeling 1981<U+2013>2009
| url = http://www.stortinget.no/no/Stortinget-og-demokratiet/Valg-og-konstituering/Valgstatistikk/Stemmefordeling/#n5 | publisher = [[Parliament of Norway|Stortinget.no]] | date = | accessdate = December 19, 2009 }}</ref> Their popularity initially declined from levels achieved by the [[Socialist Electoral League]],<ref name="seventees">{{cite web | author = | title = Stortingets sammensetning 1945-d.d. | url = http://www.nsd.uib.no/polsys/index.cfm?urlname=storting&lan=&UttakNr=108&MenuItem=N1_1&ChildItem=&State=collapse | publisher = Norsk Samfunnsvitenskapelig datatjeneste (NSD) | date = | accessdate = December 19, 2009 }}</ref> however their seat count rose to its peak after the [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 2001|2001 parliamentary election]], this election marked the Socialist Left's largest voters count, earning 12.5% of the national vote.<ref name="<U+00E5>ttinitotusenogni"/> 

When the Socialist Electoral League was founded in the early 1970s, the party managed to win voters from the Labour Party, which ruled as a [[majority government]]. Early speculations said that the Labour Party had lost 100 thousand votes to the Electoral League.<ref name="lostvotestoSV"/> The Socialist Left Party managed to gain 16 seats in Parliament.<ref name="firstandnotleast">{{cite web | author = | title = Stortingsvalget 1973. Valgte representanter etter parti. Fylke | url = http://www.ssb.no/stortingsvalg/histtab/t-1973-fylke.html | publisher = [[Statistics Norway]] | year = 2001 | accessdate = December 19, 2009 }}</ref> After the [[unification]] process was finished, the party's voter base collapsed and they earned only 4.2% of the national vote in the [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 1977|1977 parliamentary election]],<ref name="<U+00E5>ttinitotusenogni"/> and earned only two seats in parliament.<ref name="secondelection">{{cite web | author = | title = Stortingsvalget 1977. Valgte representanter etter parti. Fylke | url = http://www.ssb.no/stortingsvalg/histtab/t-1977-fylke.html | publisher = [[Statistics Norway]] | year = 2001 | accessdate = December 19, 2009 }}</ref> After the election, the party was able to win new voters, and in the [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 1989|1989 parliamentary election]], it gathered 10.1% of the national vote.<ref name="<U+00E5>ttinitotusenogni"/> After the election, the party lost voters again, and after the [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 1997|1997 election]], the party mustered 9 representatives in parliament.<ref name="meager">{{cite web | author = | title = Diverse Tillegg | url = http://www.ssb.no/stortingsvalg/valg97/addendum.shtml | publisher = [[Statistics Norway]] | date = | accessdate = December 19, 2009 }}</ref>

After having what many described as a bad [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 2001|election in 2001]], the [[Norwegian Labour Party]] lost many of its voters to the Socialist Left,<ref>{{cite news | author = Hansson, Steinar | title = Arbeiderpartiet i revers | work = [[Adresseavisen]] | date = September 29, 2001 | accessdate = December 20, 2009 | page = 15 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = | title = Arbeiderpartiet og stortingsvalget | work = [[Adresseavisen]] | date = September 18, 2001 | accessdate = December 20, 2009 | page = 34 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = | title = 1. Leder et historisk valg | work = [[Dagbladet]] | date = September 11, 2001 | accessdate = December 20, 2009 | page = 3 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = | title = Knust, men blir sittende | work = [[Aftenposten]] | date = September 11, 2001 | accessdate = December 20, 2009 | page = 1 }}</ref> with the Socialist Left increasing from a meager 6% to a 12.5% of the national vote, again becoming the fourth largest party in the country.<ref name="<U+00E5>ttinitotusenogni"/> However, this growth didn't last long, in the [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 2005|2005 election]] the party gathered 8.8% of the vote, this further decreased in the [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 2009|2009 election]] when the party gathered 6.2% of the vote.<ref name="<U+00E5>ttinitotusenogni"/>
{{-}}

=== Local elections ===
