The [[Norwegian local elections, 1975|1975 county and municipality election]] was met with a sharp decrease in voters, with the party earning a disappointing voting turnout of 5.5% in the municipal election and 5.7% in the county election.<ref name="manyelections">{{cite news | url = http://home.online.no/~b-aardal/k_f_valg.pdf | title = Elections | page = | publisher = Norsk Samfunnsvitenskapelig datatjeneste (NSD) | date = | accessdate = December 20, 2009 }}</ref> In an opinion poll done before election day in 1975, it was estimated that half of the voters who voted for the Socialist Electoral League would not vote for the party again. The decrease in voters was due the Labour Party's election surge during the [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 1973|1973 parliamentary election]].<ref>{{cite news | author = | title = Bare halvparten av SV-velgerne stemmer SV igjen | page = 1 | work = [[Verdens Gang]] | date = September 12, 1975 | accessdate = December 21, 2009 }}</ref> The party further decreased in popular support by the [[Norwegian local elections, 1979|1979 local election]], earning 4.1% in the municipal and 4.4% in the county respectively.<ref name="manyelections"/> 

However, by the [[Norwegian local elections, 1983|1983 local election]] the party increased by 1% in the municipal and 0.9% in the county election.<ref name="manyelections"/> By an opinion poll done in early September, it showed that the Labour Party would lose four of its Oslo representatives in parliament to the [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]], [[Conservative Party of Norway|Conservative Party]] and the Socialist Left.<ref>{{cite news | author = | title = H<U+00F8>yre, SV og Fr.p. sp<U+00E5>s fremgang i Oslo | page = 8 | work = [[Aftenposten]] | date = September 1, 1983 | accessdate = December 21, 2009 }}</ref> If the 1983 local election had been a parliamentary election, Socialist Left would have received 8 seats in parliament.<ref>{{cite news | author = Nilssen, Andreas | title = Valgene | page = 24 | work = [[Verdens Gang]] | date = September 16, 1983 | accessdate = December 21, 2009 }}</ref> The party earned 5.5% and 5.7% in the county and municipal election [[Norwegian local elections, 1987|in 1987]] respectively.<ref name="manyelections"/> The party's strongest county was [[Nordland]], where the party managed to gain 21.9% of the popular vote.<ref>{{cite news | author = | title = <U+00C5>mot beste SV-kommune, Nordland beste SV-fylke | page = | publisher = [[Norwegian News Agency]] | date = September 15, 1987 | accessdate = December 21, 2009 }}</ref>

The [[Norwegian local elections, 1991|1991 election]] marked a large increase in voters for the party, earning 11.6 in the municipalities and 12.2% in the counties, making the party the third-largest party in Norway.<ref name="manyelections"/> Socialist Left, along with the [[Centre Party (Norway)|Centre Party]], was named the elections "big winners" by the Norwegian press.<ref>{{cite news | author = Mathismoen, Ole | title = SV og Sp. valgets store vinnere | page = 3 | work = [[Aftenposten]] | date = September 10, 1991 | accessdate = December 21, 2009 }}</ref> In the [[Norwegian local elections, 1995|following election]], the party managed to gather 5,9% in the municipalities and 6.1% in counties.<ref name="manyelections"/> Before the [[Norwegian local elections, 1999|election in 1991]] various opinion poll showed an increase in popular support for the Socialist Left in [[Oslo]].<ref>{{cite news | author = Riisn<U+00E6>s, Ida Grieg | title = Valg 99 SV fram Oslo reddet Kristins natt | page = 10 | work = [[Dagbladet]] | date = September 14, 1999 | accessdate = December 21, 2009 }}</ref> The reason for an increase in support was that the party was again able to win votes from the Labour Party.<ref>{{cite news | author = Kluge, Lars | title = SV og H<U+00F8>yre vinner Ap.s velgere | page = 3 | work = [[Aftenposten]] | date = September 9, 1999 | accessdate = December 21, 2009 }}</ref> The party managed to gain 7.8% of the votes in the municipalities and 8.5% in the counties.<ref name="manyelections"/>

By 2003, the party's voter based had increased dramatically since 1999 local elections.<ref name="<U+00E5>ttinitotusenogni"/> The party had what many described as a "record election", winning most of its voters from the Labour Party.<ref>{{cite news | author = Nielsen, Andreas | title = SV g<U+00E5>r mot rekordvalg | page = 11 | work = [[Dagsavisen]] | date = September 15, 2003 | accessdate = December 21, 2009 }}</ref> The [[Norwegian local elections, 2007|2007 elections]] went badly for the party, and saw their voter base reduced by half from the local elections in 2003.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/innenriks/valg/val_2007/1.3434157|title=SVs oppslutning halvert|last=Helljesen|first=Vilde|coauthors=Elster, Kristian|date=September 11, 2007|publisher=NRK|language=Norwegian|accessdate=December 21, 2009}}</ref>

